Udacity investment realized a return of ~ -99% following its acquisition by Accenture, with proceeds of $11,539.66.
Uninvested capital of $1,629,843.56 was returned to investors in March 2025.
key_takeaways: The fund has a negative Net IRR of -17.46% and a Net TVPI of 0.47, indicating significant underperformance.
Four of the fund's 21 investments have exited, with three resulting in total losses (-100%) and one with a substantial loss (-64%).
The fund has distributed $258,775.68 to members, representing 1.58% of committed capital.
The investment period for the fund expired on September 17, 2022.
business_updates: Private tech and venture markets have experienced significant corrections since 2021.
There is cautious optimism for increased exit activity in the market, potentially driven by anticipated interest rate cuts.

Portfolio companies are evaluated quarterly using a methodology that considers secondary transactions, primary financing rounds with illiquidity/subordination discounts, or other relevant information.
EquityZen has adopted allocation policies to ensure fair distribution of investment opportunities between Platform Funds and the Fund.

After quarter-end, the Fund completed a credit investment in a leading outsourced marketing services provider and acquired a $17M secondary SBIC from a public pension.

Actual DPI at the fund level was 3%, with $289M called (48% of LP commitments) and distributions of $5.8M in Q3’25; a ~2% distribution by year-end is expected, reflecting portfolio yield and ongoing realizations.

Exits included the refinancing and payoff of a women’s health platform (net MOIC 1.3x, net IRR 17% on the debt position) and the exit of a California-based in-home healthcare services platform (net MOIC 1.3x and net IRR 16%; equity net MOIC 2.0x and IRR 36%).
The portfolio comprised 16 Primary, 17 Secondaries, and 20 Direct positions; the Fund’s weighted average coupon across Direct investments is ~13.2% and all positions are current on interest.
key_takeaways: Fund IV delivered a fund-level Net IRR of 11% and Net MOIC of 1.2x, outperforming the benchmark private credit return.
DPI at 3% indicates meaningful realized distributions relative to called capital, with continued expectations for higher distribution velocity.
Portfolio remains diversified across Primary, Secondary, and Direct investments, with ongoing exit activity and new investments expanding the vintage mix.
Active monetization and pipeline developments, including exits and new investments, suggest continued upside and portfolio durability.
business_updates: Four new team members joined: Yakov Belichick (Investment Team Analyst), David Hummel (Ph.D. in data science), Thomas Abraham (Senior Fund Accountant), and Nate Palumbo (Investment Team Associate).
The team is expanding to enhance execution, data capabilities, and investor relations support (noting expansion alongside Natalie on IR).
Market commentary highlights a return of M&A activity since September 2025, with larger strategic buyers entering lower-middle-market deals at attractive valuations and increased law firm activity.
Two portfolio companies are in sale processes, with potential realizations next year; several positions marked up in Q3’25 to reflect continued strong performance.

In September 2025, Fund IV committed to SBIC XVI, a Maryland-based SBIC focused on senior subordinated debt and equity to lower-middle-market businesses with $10–150M in revenue, signaling continued growth in the credit portfolio.

Revi Technologies position marked up in Q3 to $3,002,026 from $2,920,858, achieving a $16M revenue run rate.
Benefitbay position marked down in Q3 due to a lower-than-anticipated funding round, despite expecting 150% ARR growth to ~$10M by year-end.
Elife Tech position marked down slightly in Q3 to $6,836,114 from $7,151,539, now at $17M ARR.
ForwardLane position marked down in Q3 to $500,000 from $750,000.
Stage Meta position marked down in Q3 to $350,000 from $700,000.
Sayge position was written off in Q4 2023.
Vertify position marked to $0 due to an asset sale with no investor proceeds.
Qeepsake position will be marked down in Q4 following an asset sale.
Techmate posted its strongest quarter ever in Q3, generating $1.33M in revenue (up 38% year-over-year) and $64K EBITDA.
HAAS Alert ended Q3 with $8.6M contracted ARR, up 42% year-over-year.
Upflex ended Q3 with $4.0M in net ARR, up from $3.3M a year ago.
key_takeaways: Fund's overall performance metrics (TVPI 1.32x, DPI 0.00x) indicate limited realized returns despite investments dating back to 2021.
Significant positive performance from Precision Medication and Revi Technologies, both experiencing substantial markups and revenue growth.
Several portfolio companies (Sayge, Vertify, Unboxt, Careteam, ForwardLane, Stage Meta, Maya AI, 4Degrees) are underperforming, facing write-offs, markdowns, or significant operational challenges.
Elife Tech and Benefitbay show future potential but experienced recent markdowns due to funding rounds.
The fund continues to make follow-on investments, indicating ongoing support for portfolio companies.
business_updates: Fund made follow-on investments into Benefitbay and Hello Hero.
Elife Tech built out technology to add ridesharing to its platform, signed 6+ large consumer brands as channel partners, and ran successful initial market tests in South Korea and Japan.
Precision Medication is building out large new manufacturing facilities in NY and CA.
Qeepsake is undergoing an asset sale to Tinybeans Group Ltd, with proceeds expected as stock with a 24-month lockup.
Vertify completed an asset sale, resulting in no investor proceeds.
Unboxt transitioned to a self-funded model, winding down operations while maintaining the platform as a free service.
4Degrees is restructuring its engineering organization to improve technical execution after a rocky multi-region deployment led to ARR decline.
Stage Meta is pivoting its technology to focus on AI agents due to slower uptake in travel and real estate markets.
Elidah submitted Elitone for Men to the FDA and reopened its Series A to support reimbursement expansion and global distribution.
HAAS Alert is closing a $3M–$4M Series A extension to extend runway through 2026.
Maya AI will explore new product pricing and lead sourcing strategies to address a flawed unlimited usage business model.
Upflex is securing final commitments for its current equity round, which will unlock $2M in new debt, and IWG launched its first white-label deployment.
Upswot's asset sale to Uptiq closed in January 2025, with the Fund receiving preferred stock in Uptiq.

Total Net Leverage covenant of 9.25x provides significant cushion throughout the hold period
NPD revenue increased to ~5% in 2025, with a management goal to achieve ~10% by 2030
Identified upside opportunities include $1.3M incremental pricing, $0.3M Vertiv volumes, and $4M Veris opportunity for 2026E EBITDA
Pricing expected to drive ~60% of 2026P revenue growth and ~85% of 2026P EBITDA growth
key_takeaways: FDI is a leading designer and manufacturer of essential devices for power, sensing, and control in building automation systems.
The company is led by an exceptional, proven leadership team with extensive experience.
Over 75% of FDI’s demand is driven from Retrofit & Replacement (R&R).
FDI offers a portfolio of low ASP, high cost of failure components.
The company is well positioned to capture growth from macro tailwinds such as aging infrastructure, electrification, and data centers.
FDI surpasses competitors on value indicators like reliability, customer care, and lead times, while offering competitive pricing.
Strong customer retention and long-tenured revenue base, with an average top 10 customer tenure of 20+ years.
FDI's "Relay-in-a-Box" (RIB) is an industry-leading brand known for quality, reliability, and ease of installation.
Significant M&A opportunities exist in adjacent product lines and end markets.
L Squared has a proven track record of creating value in businesses similar to Functional Devices.
L Squared plans to supplement management, recruit value-added board members, invest in new product development, drive targeted pricing increases, and pursue M&A.
High visibility into 2026P results is driven by repeat customer orders from long-tenured customers with little sensitivity to price increases.
FDI maintains a strong safety record with TRIR generally at or below industry averages and low DART rates.
Employee satisfaction is above average for the industry, with competitive compensation and benefits.
business_updates: FDI sells primarily via distributors to blue-chip OEMs and end customers.
The market for peripheral components is attractive and growing, supported by aging commercial infrastructure, rapid acceleration in US energy consumption, and AI adoption fueling data center growth.
Multiple levers for growth include organic growth (market tailwinds, wallet share expansion, pricing upside, new product development) and M&A.
L Squared plans to implement AI initiatives to improve sales organization efficiency via data analysis and synthesis.
Veris is deprioritizing production of its branded current sensors and relays, creating a potential white-label opportunity for FDI.
FDI recently secured a new opportunity to supply critical components for Vertiv's Power Distribution Units (PDUs).
A new data center OEM program via Trane Technologies involves FDI supplying current sensors for their Cooling Distribution Unit line.
Data centers constitute ~15-20% of today’s commercial building market and are experiencing rapid growth due to AI adoption.
Demand for FDI’s components is consistently driven by aging building infrastructure and ongoing retrofit, renovation, and maintenance work.
Product development has been re-prioritized with key hires and an accelerated focus on new product innovation.
L Squared has identified 228 high-priority M&A targets across the fragmented peripheral components and sensors market.
There is a significant opportunity for Serviceable Addressable Market (SAM) expansion through Core FDI SAM growth, New Product Development, and M&A.
Key risks identified include potential "overstocking" by end customers, customer concentration, tariffs, and M&A execution, with mitigating factors in place.
The transaction is anticipated to sign on January 30th, 2026, with capital calls in early to mid-February and closing estimated for late February 2026.
A third-party environmental review indicates FDI's facilities have a limited environmental impact and pose a low risk.

investment_performance: The REIT continues to generate negative free cash flow after debt service, escrows, and capital requirements.
Operating performance has stabilized and occupancy has improved across much of the portfolio, but rent levels remain below expectations due to elevated supply.
S2’s base-case outlook assumes a full portfolio sale in 2030 with cumulative rent growth of approximately 16% over a five-year hold period.

Projected outcomes by tranche under S2’s base case include: New Preferred Capital ~2.26x MOIC, Converted Mezzanine ~1.85x MOIC, Participating Converted Equity ~0.82x MOIC, Non-Participating Converted Equity ~0.22x MOIC.
In several downside scenarios analyzed by Trinity, equity recovery remains limited and may be fully impaired.
An accelerated wind-down scenario, if the capital raise is unsuccessful, would most likely lead to a full loss of capital for all investor classes.
key_takeaways: The fund is seeking $70MM in additional capital to address near-term liquidity needs, including operating cash burn, accrued liabilities, and financing obligations.

The capital raise is intended to provide sufficient runway to meet obligations, avoid distressed asset sales in a soft market, and allow the portfolio time to benefit from an improving supply-demand backdrop.
The capital call is structured as a senior preferred investment at the REIT level with an 18% annual compounded preferred return, coupled with equity warrants.

Participating investors will receive penny warrants, granting them the right to acquire approximately 75% of the fully diluted equity at liquidation, significantly diluting non-participating investors.
If the capital raise is unsuccessful, the REIT will be forced to pursue an accelerated wind-down, likely resulting in sales at distressed pricing and a full loss of capital for all investor classes.
The minimum capital required to close is $30 million, which would address immediate liquidity needs but not fully resolve underlying capital structure challenges.
Trinity recommends converted mezzanine investors strongly consider participation (20-50% of invested capital) to avoid a likely loss of capital in a forced sale scenario.
Common equity/Founder’s Share investors should evaluate participation cautiously, as equity remains at risk under most scenarios, even with participation.
business_updates: S2 is seeking additional capital to address near-term liquidity needs created by a prolonged multifamily downturn.

Proceeds from the capital raise are intended for balance sheet and operating needs, including $20MM for line of credit repayment, $16MM for accrued accounts payable, $13MM for interest rate caps/reserves, $9MM for capital expenditures, $7MM for loan principal repayment, and $5MM for escrows.
The capital is not intended to fund new acquisitions or growth initiatives; the focus is on stabilization, liquidity, and preservation of existing value.

If the full $70 million is raised, Trinity expects the REIT to fully address near-term liquidity, eliminate the risk of forced asset sales, maintain operational continuity, and allow time for market fundamentals to improve.
If only the minimum $30 million is raised, the portfolio would remain vulnerable to operating volatility, and additional capital would likely be required in the future.
